      <!-- TOPIC 1: WATER -->
      <div class="topic-content active" id="topic-0">
        <div class="topic-header" data-emoji="💧">
          <div class="topic-tag">Topic 01 · Physical Chemistry</div>
          <div class="topic-title">Water in Food Systems</div>
          <div class="topic-subtitle">The most abundant and most critical molecule in food science</div>
        </div>
        <div class="cards-grid">
          <div class="card">
            <div class="card-title">Molecular Structure & Bonding</div>
            <p>Water (H₂O) has a <b>bent geometry</b> (104.5° H–O–H angle) due to two lone pairs on oxygen. The high electronegativity of O creates a significant <b>dipole moment of 1.85 D</b>, enabling extensive hydrogen bonding. Each water molecule can form up to <b>4 hydrogen bonds</b> (2 donor, 2 acceptor), with an O···O distance of ~2.8 Å and a bond energy of ~20 kJ/mol.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="card">
            <div class="card-title">Anomalous Properties</div>
            <ul>
              <li><b>High boiling point</b> (100°C vs −60°C predicted by MW) — due to H-bonding</li>
              <li><b>High specific heat capacity</b>: 4.18 J g⁻¹ °C⁻¹ (liquid)</li>
              <li><b>High latent heat of vaporisation</b>: 2257 J g⁻¹ at 100°C</li>
              <li><b>Maximum density at 4°C</b>: ice less dense than liquid water</li>
              <li><b>High dielectric constant</b>: 80.1 at 20°C — excellent solvent</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="card">
            <div class="card-title">Bound vs Free Water</div>
            <p><b>Bound water</b> (monolayer): strongly associated with polar groups; not freezable, not available as solvent; cannot support microbial growth. <b>Multilayer water</b>: less tightly held; can participate in reactions. <b>Free (bulk) water</b>: behaves like pure water; supports enzyme activity, microbial growth, and chemical reactions.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="card">
            <div class="card-title">Colligative Properties</div>
            <p>Properties dependent on <b>number of solute particles</b>, not their nature: (1) Boiling point elevation: ΔTb = Kb·m; (2) Freezing point depression: ΔTf = Kf·m (Kf = 1.86 K·kg/mol for water); (3) Osmotic pressure: π = MRT; (4) Vapour pressure lowering: ΔP/P° = xsolute (Raoult's Law). These are fundamental to food preservation and texture.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="equation-box">
          <div class="eq-label">Raoult's Law (vapour pressure lowering)</div>
          P = x_w · P°<br>
          where: P = vapour pressure of solution, x_w = mole fraction of water, P° = vapour pressure of pure water
          <div class="eq-vars">Directly related to water activity: aw = P/P° = x_w (for ideal solutions)</div>
        </div>
        <div class="highlight-box">
          <div class="hl-title">⚠ Examination Focus</div>
          <p>Understand why water's anomalous properties arise from hydrogen bonding. Be able to distinguish bound, multilayer, and free water and explain their roles in food stability. Link to water activity (Topic 8).</p>
        </div>
        <div class="ref-box">
          <div class="ref-title">Key References</div>
          <div class="ref-item" data-n="1">Damodaran, S., Parkin, K.L. & Fennema, O.R. (2017). <em>Fennema's Food Chemistry</em>, 5th ed. CRC Press. Chapter 2.</div>
          <div class="ref-item" data-n="2">Belitz, H.D., Grosch, W. & Schieberle, P. (2009). <em>Food Chemistry</em>, 4th ed. Springer. Chapter 1.</div>
          <div class="ref-item" data-n="3">Franks, F. (2000). <em>Water: A Matrix of Life</em>, 2nd ed. Royal Society of Chemistry.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- TOPIC 2: CARBOHYDRATES -->
      <div class="topic-content" id="topic-1">
        <div class="topic-header" data-emoji="🍬">
          <div class="topic-tag">Topic 02 · Carbohydrate Chemistry</div>
          <div class="topic-title">Carbohydrates</div>
          <div class="topic-subtitle">Structure, reactivity, and functional roles in foods</div>
        </div>
        <div class="cards-grid">
          <div class="card">
            <div class="card-title">Classification</div>
            <ul>
              <li><b>Monosaccharides</b>: glucose, fructose, galactose — aldoses & ketoses</li>
              <li><b>Disaccharides</b>: sucrose (α-1,2), lactose (β-1,4), maltose (α-1,4)</li>
              <li><b>Oligosaccharides</b>: DP 3–10 (e.g., raffinose, stachyose)</li>
              <li><b>Polysaccharides</b>: DP >10 — starch, cellulose, pectin, guar gum</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="card">
            <div class="card-title">Starch Structure</div>
            <p><b>Amylose</b>: linear α-(1→4) linked glucose; MW 10⁵–10⁶ Da; ~20–25% of starch; forms helical inclusion complexes with iodine (blue-black). <b>Amylopectin</b>: branched α-(1→4) with α-(1→6) branch points every 24–30 glucose units; MW 10⁷–10⁹ Da; ~75–80%; red-purple with iodine. Waxy starches: ~100% amylopectin.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="card">
            <div class="card-title">Starch Gelatinisation</div>
            <p>Irreversible swelling of starch granules in excess water on heating above the <b>gelatinisation temperature</b> (60–80°C, varies by source). Steps: water absorption → granule swelling → crystallinity loss → amylose leaching → viscosity peak → granule rupture → gel formation on cooling. Measured by <b>DSC</b> and <b>RVA</b> (Rapid Visco Analyser).</p>
          </div>
          <div class="card">
            <div class="card-title">Retrogradation</div>
            <p>Re-ordering of starch chains during cooling/storage. <b>Amylose</b> retrogradesfirst (hours; responsible for initial gel network and bread firming). <b>Amylopectin</b> retrogradelater (days–weeks; causes staling). Retrogradation is influenced by moisture, temperature, and lipid/emulsifier content. Measured by DSC endotherm at ~50–60°C.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="cards-grid">
          <div class="card">
            <div class="card-title">Maillard Reaction</div>
            <p>Non-enzymatic browning between <b>reducing sugars</b> and <b>amino groups</b> (amino acids, peptides, proteins). Three stages: (1) Initial — condensation → Schiff base → Amadori rearrangement product; (2) Intermediate — Amadori product degradation → furfurals, reductones; (3) Final — polymerisation → brown <b>melanoidins</b>. Promoted by: high temperature, low moisture (aw 0.3–0.7), alkaline pH, reactive amino acids (Lys), pentose sugars.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="card">
            <div class="card-title">Caramelisation</div>
            <p>Thermal degradation of <b>sugars without amino groups</b>. Onset temperatures: fructose 110°C, glucose 160°C, sucrose 160°C, maltose 180°C. Products: caramels (complex mixtures of oligomers, polymers), volatile compounds (furanones, diacetyl), brown pigments. Reactions: dehydration, cyclisation, polymerisation, fragmentation.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="highlight-box">
          <div class="hl-title">Key Distinction</div>
          <p><b>Maillard reaction</b> requires a nitrogen source (amino acids/proteins) + reducing sugars. <b>Caramelisation</b> is purely sugar pyrolysis — no nitrogen required. Both produce brown colours and flavour compounds but through different mechanisms.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="ref-box">
          <div class="ref-title">Key References</div>
          <div class="ref-item" data-n="1">BeMiller, J.N. (2019). <em>Carbohydrate Chemistry for Food Scientists</em>, 3rd ed. AACC International Press.</div>
          <div class="ref-item" data-n="2">Damodaran et al. (2017). Chapter 3 — Carbohydrates.</div>
          <div class="ref-item" data-n="3">van der Maarel, M.J.E.C. et al. (2002). Properties and applications of starch-converting enzymes. <em>J. Biotechnol.</em> 94, 137–155.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- TOPIC 3: GELATION -->
      <div class="topic-content" id="topic-2">
        <div class="topic-header" data-emoji="🌊">
          <div class="topic-tag">Topic 03 · Colloid Science</div>
          <div class="topic-title">Gelation</div>
          <div class="topic-subtitle">Network formation, gel structure, and rheological behaviour</div>
        </div>
        <div class="cards-grid">
          <div class="card">
            <div class="card-title">What is a Gel?</div>
            <p>A gel is a <b>viscoelastic semi-solid</b>: a three-dimensional network that immobilises a liquid phase. Gels exhibit solid-like elastic behaviour (G' > G") at rest but can flow under stress. Characterised by: gel strength (storage modulus G'), gelation temperature, melting temperature, and reversibility.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="card">
            <div class="card-title">Physical vs Chemical Gels</div>
            <p><b>Physical gels</b>: held by non-covalent interactions (H-bonds, hydrophobic, ionic, van der Waals). Often thermoreversible (e.g., gelatin, agar, pectin). <b>Chemical gels</b>: formed by covalent cross-links. Irreversible (e.g., heat-set protein gels, enzyme cross-linked gels). Most food gels are physical.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="card">
            <div class="card-title">Gelatin</div>
            <p>Derived from collagen (partial hydrolysis of triple helix). On cooling, partial re-formation of <b>triple helices</b> (junction zones) creates network. Sol-gel transition at ~30–35°C (near body temperature — melt-in-mouth). Gel strength measured in <b>Bloom number</b> (g; 50–300). Concentration for gel: ≥1% w/w. Impaired by: low concentration, high temperature, extreme pH, proteases.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="card">
            <div class="card-title">Pectin Gelation</div>
            <p><b>High-methoxyl pectin (HM, DE>50%)</b>: gels at low pH (<3.5) and high sugar (>55°Brix) via hydrophobic interactions and H-bonds — junction zones between partially demethylated regions. <b>Low-methoxyl pectin (LM, DE<50%)</b>: gels with divalent cations (Ca²⁺) via the <b>egg-box model</b> — Ca²⁺ cross-links guluronate/galacturonate sequences. Independent of pH and sugar.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="card">
            <div class="card-title">Agar & Carrageenan</div>
            <p><b>Agar</b>: agarose + agaropectin extracted from red algae. Gels by double helix (coil→helix) transition at ~40°C; melts at ~85°C. Large hysteresis. <b>ι-Carrageenan</b>: ionic gel with Ca²⁺; elastic, thixotropic. <b>κ-Carrageenan</b>: brittle gel; synergistic with locust bean gum. <b>λ-Carrageenan</b>: does not gel; thickener only.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="card">
            <div class="card-title">Protein Gels</div>
            <p>Heat-set protein gels: denaturation → unfolding → aggregation → network. <b>Fine-stranded gels</b> (low ionic strength, pH far from pI): transparent, elastic. <b>Particulate gels</b> (high ionic strength or near pI): opaque, brittle. Key proteins: whey proteins (β-lactoglobulin), soy proteins, egg white (ovalbumin), myosin (meat gels).</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="equation-box">
          <div class="eq-label">Gel Rheology (Small Amplitude Oscillatory Shear)</div>
          G* = G' + iG''<br>
          tan δ = G''/G' (loss tangent)<br>
          <div class="eq-vars">G' = storage (elastic) modulus; G'' = loss (viscous) modulus; tan δ < 1 indicates gel-like behaviour</div>
        </div>
        <div class="ref-box">
          <div class="ref-title">Key References</div>
          <div class="ref-item" data-n="1">Phillips, G.O. & Williams, P.A. (eds) (2009). <em>Handbook of Hydrocolloids</em>, 2nd ed. Woodhead.</div>
          <div class="ref-item" data-n="2">Nishinari, K. (1997). Rheological and DSC study of sol-gel transition in aqueous dispersions. <em>Colloid Polym. Sci.</em> 275, 1093–1107.</div>
          <div class="ref-item" data-n="3">Damodaran et al. (2017). Chapter 12 — Dispersed Systems.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- TOPIC 4: PROTEINS -->
      <div class="topic-content" id="topic-3">
        <div class="topic-header" data-emoji="🧬">
          <div class="topic-tag">Topic 04 · Protein Chemistry</div>
          <div class="topic-title">Proteins in Food Systems</div>
          <div class="topic-subtitle">Structure, denaturation, and functional properties</div>
        </div>
        <div class="cards-grid">
          <div class="card">
            <div class="card-title">Structural Hierarchy</div>
            <ul>
              <li><b>Primary</b>: amino acid sequence; peptide bonds; determined by DNA</li>
              <li><b>Secondary</b>: α-helix (3.6 residues/turn, H-bonds i to i+4), β-sheet (parallel/antiparallel, H-bonds between strands), β-turns, random coil</li>
              <li><b>Tertiary</b>: 3D folding; stabilised by disulfide bonds, H-bonds, hydrophobic interactions, electrostatic/salt bridges, van der Waals</li>
              <li><b>Quaternary</b>: assembly of multiple polypeptides (subunits)</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="card">
            <div class="card-title">Denaturation</div>
            <p>Loss of higher-order structure without hydrolysis of peptide bonds. Causes: <b>Heat</b> (disrupts H-bonds, increases hydrophobic effect entropy), <b>pH extremes</b> (alter ionisation, disrupt electrostatic interactions), <b>Chaotropic agents</b> (urea, guanidinium HCl), <b>Organic solvents</b>, <b>High pressure</b>. Usually irreversible in food processing. Enthalpy change measured by DSC (denaturation temperature Td, enthalpy ΔHd).</p>
          </div>
          <div class="card">
            <div class="card-title">Isoelectric Point (pI)</div>
            <p>The pH at which net charge = 0 and <b>protein solubility is minimum</b>. Important because: (1) Protein precipitates at pI (used in isoelectric precipitation of casein at pH 4.6); (2) Emulsification and foaming are lowest at pI; (3) Electrophoretic mobility = 0. pI values: casein ~4.6, β-lactoglobulin ~5.2, ovalbumin ~4.7, myosin ~5.4, soy 11S ~4.6.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="card">
            <div class="card-title">Functional Properties</div>
            <ul>
              <li><b>Solubility</b>: NSI (Nitrogen Solubility Index); affects all functions</li>
              <li><b>Water holding capacity</b>: critical in meat, dairy</li>
              <li><b>Gelation</b>: heat-set or cold-set; WHC, texture</li>
              <li><b>Emulsification</b>: adsorption at oil-water interface; surface hydrophobicity key</li>
              <li><b>Foaming</b>: adsorption at air-water interface; flexibility vs rigidity tradeoff</li>
              <li><b>Maillard browning</b>: ε-amino group of Lys most reactive</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="two-col">
          <div class="highlight-box">
            <div class="hl-title">Surface Hydrophobicity</div>
            <p>A key determinant of emulsification and foaming. Measured by fluorescent probes (ANS, CPA) or hydrophobic interaction chromatography. Partial denaturation can expose hydrophobic residues and improve functional properties — the basis for protein modification technologies.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="highlight-box">
            <div class="hl-title">Disulfide Bonds</div>
            <p>Covalent cross-links between Cys residues. Critical in gluten network (gliadin + glutenin) — disulfide interchange during dough mixing creates viscoelastic network. Thiol–disulfide exchange catalysed by SSL and DATEM in breadmaking.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="ref-box">
          <div class="ref-title">Key References</div>
          <div class="ref-item" data-n="1">Damodaran et al. (2017). Chapter 5 — Amino Acids, Peptides, and Proteins.</div>
          <div class="ref-item" data-n="2">Belitz et al. (2009). Chapter 1 — Amino Acids, Peptides, and Proteins.</div>
          <div class="ref-item" data-n="3">Kinsella, J.E. (1976). Functional properties of food proteins. <em>CRC Crit. Rev. Food Sci. Nutr.</em> 7, 219–280.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- TOPIC 5: GLASS TRANSITION -->
      <div class="topic-content" id="topic-4">
        <div class="topic-header" data-emoji="🔬">
          <div class="topic-tag">Topic 05 · Physical State</div>
          <div class="topic-title">Glass Transition Temperature</div>
          <div class="topic-subtitle">Amorphous state physics and food stability</div>
        </div>
        <div class="cards-grid">
          <div class="card">
            <div class="card-title">Amorphous vs Crystalline</div>
            <p><b>Crystalline</b>: long-range molecular order; sharp melting point (Tm); lower free energy. <b>Amorphous</b>: disordered; no sharp melting point. Below Tg → <b>glassy state</b> (rigid, brittle, very high viscosity ~10¹² Pa·s). Above Tg → <b>rubbery state</b> (mobile, viscoelastic, ~10⁸–10⁹ Pa·s). Most freeze-dried and spray-dried foods are amorphous.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="card">
            <div class="card-title">WLF Equation</div>
            <div class="eq-label" style="font-size:0.7rem;color:var(--text-muted);margin-bottom:6px;">Williams-Landel-Ferry (1955)</div>
            <div style="font-family:'JetBrains Mono';font-size:0.85rem;color:var(--accent2);line-height:1.8">log(aT) = −C₁(T − Tg) / (C₂ + T − Tg)</div>
            <p style="font-size:0.83rem;margin-top:10px;line-height:1.6">Universal constants (at Tg): C₁ = 17.44, C₂ = 51.6 K. aT = ratio of relaxation times. Predicts <b>dramatic increase in molecular mobility</b> above Tg — reaction rates increase orders of magnitude.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="card">
            <div class="card-title">Plasticisation by Water</div>
            <p>Water is the most potent plasticiser in food: it increases free volume → <b>lowers Tg</b>. The Gordon–Taylor equation predicts Tg of mixtures: Tg = (w₁Tg₁ + kw₂Tg₂)/(w₁ + kw₂). For anhydrous sucrose Tg ≈ 65°C; at aw = 0.33, Tg ≈ 25°C. Below Tg the material is stable; above Tg reactions accelerate (crystallisation, collapse, stickiness).</p>
          </div>
          <div class="card">
            <div class="card-title">Food Stability Implications</div>
            <ul>
              <li><b>Caking</b>: powder above Tg → viscous flow → particle fusion (spray-dried powders)</li>
              <li><b>Crystallisation</b>: amorphous lactose crystallises above Tg at aw>0.3</li>
              <li><b>Crispness loss</b>: extruded snacks soften above Tg at high aw</li>
              <li><b>Freeze-drying</b>: collapse temperature ≈ Tg of maximally freeze-concentrated solution (Tg')</li>
              <li><b>Maillard reaction</b>: greatly accelerated above Tg</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="highlight-box">
          <div class="hl-title">Tg Measurement</div>
          <p>Primarily by <b>Differential Scanning Calorimetry (DSC)</b>: detected as a step change in heat capacity (Cp) baseline — not a peak like melting. Also measured by Dynamic Mechanical Analysis (DMA), Dielectric Analysis, and Thermomechanical Analysis (TMA).</p>
        </div>
        <div class="ref-box">
          <div class="ref-title">Key References</div>
          <div class="ref-item" data-n="1">Slade, L. & Levine, H. (1991). Beyond water activity: Recent advances. <em>CRC Crit. Rev. Food Sci. Nutr.</em> 30, 115–360.</div>
          <div class="ref-item" data-n="2">Roos, Y.H. (1995). <em>Phase Transitions in Foods</em>. Academic Press.</div>
          <div class="ref-item" data-n="3">Williams, M.L., Landel, R.F. & Ferry, J.D. (1955). The temperature dependence of relaxation mechanisms. <em>J. Am. Chem. Soc.</em> 77, 3701–3707.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- TOPIC 6: SWEETENERS -->
      <div class="topic-content" id="topic-5">
        <div class="topic-header" data-emoji="🍯">
          <div class="topic-tag">Topic 06 · Sensory Chemistry</div>
          <div class="topic-title">Food Sweeteners</div>
          <div class="topic-subtitle">Natural and high-intensity sweeteners, receptor mechanisms</div>
        </div>
        <div class="cards-grid">
          <div class="card">
            <div class="card-title">Sweet Taste Receptor</div>
            <p>Sweetness is perceived via the <b>T1R2/T1R3 heterodimer</b>, a G protein-coupled receptor (GPCR). The receptor has a large extracellular Venus flytrap domain (VFD) on T1R2 where sugars and sweeteners bind, and a cysteine-rich domain (CRD) + transmembrane domain (TMD) for some high-intensity sweeteners (e.g., cyclamate). Signal transduction via <b>α-gustducin → PLC → IP₃ → Ca²⁺ release → TRPM5 → depolarisation</b>.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="card">
            <div class="card-title">AH/B/X Theory</div>
            <p>Shallenberger & Acree (1967): sweetness requires an <b>AH-B system</b> — a proton donor (AH) and electronegative acceptor (B) separated by ~2.5–4 Å, which H-bonds to a complementary site on the receptor. Kier (1972) extended to AH/B/X: X = hydrophobic binding site. Explains why many different molecules taste sweet. Not sufficient to explain all sweeteners — superseded by structural biology of T1R2/T1R3.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="table-wrap">
          <table>
            <tr><th>Sweetener</th><th>Type</th><th>Relative Sweetness (sucrose=1)</th><th>Energy (kcal/g)</th><th>Notes</th></tr>
            <tr><td>Sucrose</td><td>Natural</td><td>1.0</td><td>4</td><td>Reference standard</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Fructose</td><td>Natural</td><td>1.2–1.8</td><td>4</td><td>Sweeter cold; used in HFCS</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Glucose</td><td>Natural</td><td>0.7–0.8</td><td>4</td><td>Directly fermentable</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Lactose</td><td>Natural</td><td>0.2–0.4</td><td>4</td><td>Milk sugar; low sweetness</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Sorbitol</td><td>Sugar alcohol</td><td>0.5–0.7</td><td>2.6</td><td>Humectant; laxative effect >50g</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Xylitol</td><td>Sugar alcohol</td><td>~1.0</td><td>2.4</td><td>Cooling effect; dental caries prevention</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Acesulfame-K</td><td>Artificial</td><td>~200</td><td>0</td><td>Heat stable; often blended</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Aspartame</td><td>Artificial</td><td>180–200</td><td>~0</td><td>Unstable at high T/pH; PKU warning</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Saccharin</td><td>Artificial</td><td>300–500</td><td>0</td><td>Bitter metallic aftertaste</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Sucralose</td><td>Artificial</td><td>600</td><td>0</td><td>Chlorinated sucrose; heat stable</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Steviol glycosides</td><td>Natural-derived</td><td>200–400</td><td>0</td><td>From <em>Stevia rebaudiana</em>; rebaudioside A cleanest</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Thaumatin</td><td>Protein</td><td>2000–3000</td><td>4</td><td>Protein sweetener; flavour modifier</td></tr>
          </table>
        </div>
        <div class="highlight-box">
          <div class="hl-title">Synergy</div>
          <p>Blending sweeteners (e.g., acesulfame-K + aspartame; sucralose + sugar) often produces <b>synergistic sweetness</b> — the mixture is sweeter than the sum of parts. This allows reduction in total sweetener use and improved sensory profile (masking aftertastes).</p>
        </div>
        <div class="ref-box">
          <div class="ref-title">Key References</div>
          <div class="ref-item" data-n="1">Shallenberger, R.S. & Acree, T.E. (1967). Molecular theory of sweet taste. <em>Nature</em> 216, 480–482.</div>
          <div class="ref-item" data-n="2">Lim, J. (2011). Hedonic scaling: A review of methods and theory. <em>Food Qual. Prefer.</em> 22, 733–747.</div>
          <div class="ref-item" data-n="3">Damodaran et al. (2017). Chapter 9 — Sweeteners.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- TOPIC 7: ENZYMES -->
      <div class="topic-content" id="topic-6">
        <div class="topic-header" data-emoji="⚗️">
          <div class="topic-tag">Topic 07 · Biochemistry</div>
          <div class="topic-title">Food Enzymes</div>
          <div class="topic-subtitle">Kinetics, food applications, and control strategies</div>
        </div>
        <div class="cards-grid">
          <div class="card">
            <div class="card-title">Michaelis-Menten Kinetics</div>
            <div class="equation-box" style="margin:0 0 10px">
              v = V<sub>max</sub>[S] / (K<sub>m</sub> + [S])
            </div>
            <ul>
              <li><b>Vmax</b>: maximum velocity (enzyme saturated); Vmax = kcat·[E]T</li>
              <li><b>Km</b>: Michaelis constant = [S] at v = Vmax/2; reflects enzyme-substrate affinity (low Km = high affinity)</li>
              <li><b>kcat</b> (turnover number): mol substrate converted per mol enzyme per sec</li>
              <li><b>kcat/Km</b>: specificity constant; measure of catalytic efficiency</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="card">
            <div class="card-title">Enzyme Inhibition</div>
            <ul>
              <li><b>Competitive</b>: inhibitor binds active site; apparent Km increases, Vmax unchanged; overcome by excess [S]</li>
              <li><b>Uncompetitive</b>: inhibitor binds only ES complex; both Km and Vmax decrease (same Vmax/Km)</li>
              <li><b>Non-competitive</b>: inhibitor binds E or ES; Vmax decreases, Km unchanged (pure) or changes (mixed)</li>
              <li><b>Irreversible</b>: covalent modification of active site residue</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="card">
            <div class="card-title">Temperature & pH Effects</div>
            <p>Rate doubles per 10°C rise (Q10 ≈ 2) up to optimal temperature, then drops sharply due to denaturation. Arrhenius equation: k = A·e^(−Ea/RT). pH optimum varies: pepsin pH 2, amylase pH 6–7, trypsin pH 8. Extremes alter ionisation of active site residues (His, Asp, Glu, Cys, Lys) and protein conformation.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="card">
            <div class="card-title">Polyphenol Oxidase (PPO)</div>
            <p>Cu-containing enzyme. Catalyses: <b>phenols → o-quinones</b> → brown polymers (enzymatic browning). Requires O₂. Substrate: chlorogenic acid (apple, potato), catechins (tea). Prevention: (1) blanching, (2) acidification (pH<4), (3) sulfite/ascorbate addition, (4) chelation (EDTA), (5) modified atmosphere (low O₂), (6) cold storage.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="card">
            <div class="card-title">Food-Relevant Enzymes</div>
            <ul>
              <li><b>α-Amylase</b>: endo-cleaves α-(1→4); bread volume, starch liquefaction</li>
              <li><b>Protease</b>: cheese ripening (chymosin), meat tenderisation (papain, bromelain)</li>
              <li><b>Lipase</b>: cheese flavour (fatty acids); rancidity in cereals</li>
              <li><b>Lipoxygenase</b>: oxidises PUFAs → off-flavours; bleaches flour (desirable)</li>
              <li><b>Pectinase</b>: fruit juice clarification, wine processing</li>
              <li><b>Transglutaminase</b>: cross-links Gln-Lys; restructured meat, improved dough</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="card">
            <div class="card-title">Lineweaver-Burk Plot</div>
            <p>Double reciprocal plot: <b>1/v vs 1/[S]</b>. Linear transformation of Michaelis-Menten: 1/v = (Km/Vmax)·(1/[S]) + 1/Vmax. Slope = Km/Vmax; y-intercept = 1/Vmax; x-intercept = −1/Km. Used to determine inhibition type and kinetic constants, though prone to error at low [S]. Modern: non-linear regression preferred.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="ref-box">
          <div class="ref-title">Key References</div>
          <div class="ref-item" data-n="1">Whitaker, J.R. (1994). <em>Principles of Enzymology for the Food Sciences</em>, 2nd ed. Marcel Dekker.</div>
          <div class="ref-item" data-n="2">Damodaran et al. (2017). Chapter 7 — Enzymes.</div>
          <div class="ref-item" data-n="3">Vámos-Vigyázó, L. (1981). Polyphenol oxidase and peroxidase in fruits and vegetables. <em>CRC Crit. Rev. Food Sci. Nutr.</em> 15, 49–127.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- TOPIC 8: WATER ACTIVITY -->
      <div class="topic-content" id="topic-7">
        <div class="topic-header" data-emoji="📊">
          <div class="topic-tag">Topic 08 · Physical Chemistry</div>
          <div class="topic-title">Water Activity</div>
          <div class="topic-subtitle">Thermodynamic measure of water availability in foods</div>
        </div>
        <div class="cards-grid">
          <div class="card">
            <div class="card-title">Definition & Measurement</div>
            <div class="equation-box" style="margin:0 0 10px">a<sub>w</sub> = p/p° = ERH/100
            </div>
            <p style="font-size:0.85rem;line-height:1.6">p = partial pressure of water vapour above food; p° = vapour pressure of pure water at same T. Equivalent to <b>Equilibrium Relative Humidity (ERH)/100</b>. Range: 0 (anhydrous) to 1.0 (pure water). Measured by <b>chilled mirror dew point hygrometry</b> (most accurate) or capacitance sensors.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="card">
            <div class="card-title">Sorption Isotherms</div>
            <p>Relationship between aw and moisture content at constant T. <b>Type II sigmoid</b> isotherm typical for foods. Three regions: (1) <b>Monolayer region</b> (aw 0–0.25): tightly bound water; most stable; (2) <b>Multilayer region</b> (aw 0.25–0.7): dissolution of solutes; (3) <b>Capillary/free water</b> (aw >0.7): free water; microbial growth. <b>Hysteresis</b>: desorption > adsorption isotherm (due to capillary effects, polymer matrix changes).</p>
          </div>
          <div class="card">
            <div class="card-title">BET Equation</div>
            <div class="equation-box" style="margin:0 0 10px;font-size:0.8rem">
              aw / [m(1−aw)] = 1/(m₀C) + (C−1)/(m₀C) · aw
            </div>
            <p style="font-size:0.85rem;line-height:1.6">Brunauer-Emmett-Teller: m = moisture content, m₀ = <b>monolayer moisture content</b>, C = constant related to binding energy. Monolayer: most stable moisture content; maximum shelf life. Plot aw/[m(1-aw)] vs aw → slope and intercept give m₀ and C.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="card">
            <div class="card-title">Microbial Stability</div>
            <ul>
              <li>Most spoilage bacteria: aw <b>≥ 0.91</b></li>
              <li>Most yeasts: aw <b>≥ 0.88</b></li>
              <li>Most moulds: aw <b>≥ 0.70–0.80</b></li>
              <li>Xerophilic moulds (e.g., <em>Aspergillus</em>): aw <b>≥ 0.61</b></li>
              <li><em>S. aureus</em> (toxin): aw <b>≥ 0.86</b></li>
              <li><em>C. botulinum</em> (type A/B): aw <b>≥ 0.93</b></li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="table-wrap">
          <table>
            <tr><th>aw Range</th><th>Chemical Reactions</th><th>Example Foods</th></tr>
            <tr><td>0.95–1.0</td><td>All reactions active; microbial growth</td><td>Fresh meat, fish, vegetables</td></tr>
            <tr><td>0.80–0.95</td><td>Maillard fast; enzymatic browning; oxidation</td><td>Processed cheese, cured meats, jam</td></tr>
            <tr><td>0.60–0.80</td><td>Maillard moderate; lipid oxidation increasing</td><td>Dry fruits, flour, cereals</td></tr>
            <tr><td>0.30–0.60</td><td>Maillard minimum; lipid oxidation begins</td><td>Crackers, cookies</td></tr>
            <tr><td>0–0.30</td><td>Lipid oxidation high; very low reaction rates</td><td>Freeze-dried foods, anhydrous</td></tr>
          </table>
        </div>
        <div class="ref-box">
          <div class="ref-title">Key References</div>
          <div class="ref-item" data-n="1">Labuza, T.P. (1980). The effect of water activity on reaction kinetics. <em>Food Technol.</em> 34(4), 36–41.</div>
          <div class="ref-item" data-n="2">Damodaran et al. (2017). Chapter 2 — Water and Ice.</div>
          <div class="ref-item" data-n="3">Van den Berg, C. & Bruin, S. (1981). Water activity and its estimation in food systems. In: <em>Water Activity: Influences on Food Quality</em>. Academic Press.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- TOPIC 9: COLOUR CHEMISTRY -->
      <div class="topic-content" id="topic-8">
        <div class="topic-header" data-emoji="🌈">
          <div class="topic-tag">Topic 09 · Pigment Chemistry</div>
          <div class="topic-title">Food Colour Chemistry</div>
          <div class="topic-subtitle">Natural pigments: structure, stability, and transformations</div>
        </div>
        <div class="cards-grid">
          <div class="card">
            <div class="card-title">Chlorophylls</div>
            <p>Green pigments in all photosynthetic plant tissues. <b>Chlorophyll a</b> (blue-green, λmax 430/663 nm) and <b>b</b> (yellow-green, λmax 453/642 nm). Porphyrin ring with central <b>Mg²⁺</b>. Phytol tail confers hydrophobicity. On heating/acidification: Mg²⁺ → H⁺ → <b>olive-green pheophytin</b>. Further hydrolysis → pheophorbide. Preservation: alkaline blanching (adds Mg²⁺), copper chlorophyllin (approved additive E141).</p>
          </div>
          <div class="card">
            <div class="card-title">Carotenoids</div>
            <p>Polyene pigments: C₄₀ terpenoids with conjugated double-bond chromophore. <b>Carotenes</b> (hydrocarbons): β-carotene (orange, λmax ~450 nm), lycopene (red, λmax ~470 nm). <b>Xanthophylls</b> (oxygenated): lutein, zeaxanthin, astaxanthin (salmon). Cis/trans isomerisation on processing → loss of colour intensity. Prooxidant at high concentrations; antioxidant at low. Lipid-soluble → stable to acid/base but sensitive to light and oxygen.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="card">
            <div class="card-title">Anthocyanins</div>
            <p>Water-soluble flavonoid pigments (glycosides of anthocyanidins). Colour highly <b>pH-dependent</b>: pH<3 → flavylium cation (<b>red</b>); pH 4–5 → carbinol base (colourless); pH 6–7 → quinonoidal base (<b>blue/purple</b>); pH>8 → chalcone (yellow). Also affected by: co-pigmentation (+stability), metal complexation (Fe³⁺, Al³⁺ → blue), temperature, light, SO₂. ~700 known; found in berries, red cabbage, grape, elderberry.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="card">
            <div class="card-title">Myoglobin & Meat Colour</div>
            <p>Heme protein (MW 16,700 Da); Fe in porphyrin ring. Three forms: <b>Deoxymyoglobin</b> (Fe²⁺, no ligand): purple-red; <b>Oxymyoglobin</b> (Fe²⁺, O₂): bright red (desirable); <b>Metmyoglobin</b> (Fe³⁺): brown (oxidised, undesirable). Interconversion: reducing conditions maintain Fe²⁺; high O₂ → oxymyoglobin; moderate/low O₂ → metmyoglobin. MAP: high-O₂ (70–80%) maintains oxymyoglobin; CO + low-O₂ maintains red colour (some markets).</p>
          </div>
          <div class="card">
            <div class="card-title">Betalains</div>
            <p>N-containing pigments unique to order Caryophyllales (beetroot, cactus pear, amaranth). <b>Betacyanins</b> (red-violet, λmax ~540 nm): betanin (most common). <b>Betaxanthins</b> (yellow-orange, λmax ~480 nm): vulgaxanthin. Not co-occurring with anthocyanins. Stable at pH 3–7; sensitive to heat, light, O₂. Used as natural food colourants (E162).</p>
          </div>
          <div class="card">
            <div class="card-title">Curcumin & Other Pigments</div>
            <p><b>Curcumin</b> (turmeric): yellow diketone; pH-sensitive (yellow → orange-red >pH 8); light-sensitive; E100. <b>Riboflavin</b>: yellow flavin; E101. <b>Caramel</b>: Maillard-derived brown (E150). <b>Annatto</b> (bixin, norbixin from <em>Bixa orellana</em>): yellow-orange; E160b. <b>Paprika</b> (capsanthin, capsorubin): red carotenoids; E160c.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="ref-box">
          <div class="ref-title">Key References</div>
          <div class="ref-item" data-n="1">Hendry, G.A.F. & Houghton, J.D. (eds) (1996). <em>Natural Food Colorants</em>, 2nd ed. Blackie Academic.</div>
          <div class="ref-item" data-n="2">Damodaran et al. (2017). Chapter 10 — Colorants.</div>
          <div class="ref-item" data-n="3">Stintzing, F.C. & Carle, R. (2004). Functional properties of anthocyanins and betalains. <em>Trends Food Sci. Technol.</em> 15, 19–38.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- TOPIC 10: COLOUR MEASUREMENT -->
      <div class="topic-content" id="topic-9">
        <div class="topic-header" data-emoji="📐">
          <div class="topic-tag">Topic 10 · Analytical Methods</div>
          <div class="topic-title">Colour Measurement</div>
          <div class="topic-subtitle">CIELAB, colorimetry, and spectrophotometry in food analysis</div>
        </div>
        <div class="cards-grid">
          <div class="card">
            <div class="card-title">CIE XYZ Colour Space (1931)</div>
            <p>The CIE (Commission Internationale de l'Éclairage) tristimulus system. <b>X, Y, Z</b> are virtual primaries derived from human cone responses. Y ≈ luminance (perceived lightness). CIE chromaticity coordinates: x = X/(X+Y+Z), y = Y/(X+Y+Z). Foundation for all modern colour spaces. Dependent on: illuminant (D65 = daylight standard for food), standard observer (2°, 10°), and geometry (0°/45° or integrating sphere).</p>
          </div>
          <div class="card">
            <div class="card-title">CIELAB (L*a*b*) Colour Space</div>
            <ul>
              <li><b>L*</b> (0–100): lightness; 0 = black, 100 = white</li>
              <li><b>a*</b>: green (−) to red (+); range ≈ −128 to +127</li>
              <li><b>b*</b>: blue (−) to yellow (+); range ≈ −128 to +127</li>
              <li><b>Chroma</b>: C*ab = √(a*² + b*²) — saturation/vividness</li>
              <li><b>Hue angle</b>: h°ab = arctan(b*/a*); 0° = red, 90° = yellow, 180° = green, 270° = blue</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="equation-box">
          <div class="eq-label">CIELAB Colour Difference (ΔE*ab)</div>
          ΔE*ab = √[ (ΔL*)² + (Δa*)² + (Δb*)² ]<br>
          <div class="eq-vars">ΔE*ab &lt;1: imperceptible; 1–2: barely perceptible; 2–3.5: perceptible; &gt;3.5: clearly visible colour difference</div>
        </div>
        <div class="cards-grid">
          <div class="card">
            <div class="card-title">Instruments</div>
            <ul>
              <li><b>Colorimeter</b>: measures filtered L*, a*, b* directly; inexpensive; less versatile</li>
              <li><b>Spectrophotometer/Spectroradiometer</b>: measures full reflectance spectrum (360–780 nm); calculates any colour space; most versatile and accurate</li>
              <li><b>Hunter Lab colorimeter</b>: older scale (L, a, b; slightly different formulae); still used in industry; not identical to CIELAB</li>
              <li><b>Imaging colorimetry</b>: multi- or hyperspectral imaging; spatial colour distribution</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="card">
            <div class="card-title">Measurement Geometry</div>
            <p><b>0°/45°</b> (or 45°/0°): illuminates at 0°, measures at 45°; excludes specular (mirror) reflection; measures colour as perceived visually. <b>d/8° (integrating sphere)</b>: diffuse illumination; can include (SPIN) or exclude (SPEX) specular; better for heterogeneous foods. Choice affects results — report geometry, illuminant, and observer with all colour data. <b>SPIN vs SPEX</b>: SPIN used for opacity/translucency, SPEX for surface colour.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="card">
            <div class="card-title">Transmittance vs Reflectance</div>
            <p><b>Reflectance</b>: used for opaque/solid foods (meat, bread, cheese). <b>Transmittance</b>: for clear/translucent liquids (fruit juice, wine, beer); measured as absorbance: A = −log₁₀(T). <b>Total appearance</b>: includes gloss, haze, translucency. For liquids, the <b>Beer-Lambert law</b> applies: A = εcl (ε = molar extinction coefficient, c = concentration, l = path length).</p>
          </div>
          <div class="card">
            <div class="card-title">CIEDE2000 (ΔE₀₀)</div>
            <p>Advanced colour difference formula (ISO/CIE 2014). Corrects for non-uniformity of CIELAB space particularly in blue, chroma, and lightness regions. Adds weighting functions: kL, kC, kH and interactive terms RT (rotation term for blue). <b>Recommended for food colour difference calculations</b> where high precision is needed (e.g., process control, sensory correlation).</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="ref-box">
          <div class="ref-title">Key References</div>
          <div class="ref-item" data-n="1">MacDougall, D.B. (ed.) (2002). <em>Colour in Food</em>. Woodhead Publishing.</div>
          <div class="ref-item" data-n="2">Leon, K. et al. (2006). Color measurement in L*, a*, b* units from RGB digital images. <em>Food Res. Int.</em> 39, 1084–1091.</div>
          <div class="ref-item" data-n="3">CIE (2004). <em>Colorimetry</em>, 3rd ed. Publication 15:2004. CIE Central Bureau, Vienna.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

    </main>
  </div>
</div>
